dalai 's special envoys meet with chinese officials behind closed doors 
cgp beili 
dalai 's special envoys meet with chinese officials behind closed doors . 
the dalai lama stressed that he wants autonomy , not independence , for tibet . 
the special envoys of the dalai lama , tibet 's spiritual leader in exile , are having closed - door meetings with chinese officials in beijing with no details released . 
this is $number official meeting between china and the dalai 's government - in - exile since contacts resumed $date . 
however , as always , the two sides met behind close doors with no details revealed . 
reporters said that the two sides held talks several times but so far no substantive results have been achieved . 
the dalai lama , who is in exile in northern india , said that he wants autonomy , not independence , for tibet . 
the chinese side refused to comment on the bilateral talks . 
however , analysts said that beijing wanted to have the dialogue partly because it is worried that tibetans ' dissatisfaction with the chinese rule may escalate should this $number - year - old spiritual leader in exile die . 
cultural identity 
the delegation of dalai 's government - in - exile was led by lodi gyaltsen gyari , who was also chief representative to several previous talks . 
a spokesperson for the tibetan government - in - exile said that the several rounds of talks they had with chinese officials in switzerland $date were very " close and frank , " bringing hopes for tibetans . 
the spokesperson said that their ultimate hope is to resolve the relevant issues on the basis reached through negotiation with the chinese leadership so that tibetans will have the freedom to preserve their cultural identity , which they consider important . 
cgp beili 
dalai lama 's special envoys reiterate they do not seek tibet 's independence . 
the dalai lama will go to visit washington this month . 
prior to the tibetan spiritual leader dalai lama 's visit to the united states on $date , his special envoys said that the tibetan government - in - exile would not demand for tibet 's independence . 
lodi gyaltsen gyari said in washington that he hoped the chinese government would indeed preserve tibet 's unique culture and tradition . 
during his visit to the us next week , the dalai lama is expected to discuss the tibetan issue with president bush in hopes that bush can urge the chinese government to give tibet genuine autonomy . 
dalai 's representative had direct contact with beijing officials for $number time in berne in $date of this year . 
" genuine autonomy " 
lodi gyaltsen gyari noted that in recent years the tibetan government - in - exile has seen some positive aspects when meeting with chinese authorities . 
the dalai lama 's special envoys found that beijing leaders , especially the representatives from the united front work department of the cpc central committee , were more willing than before to hear their opinions . 
however , lodi gyaltsen gyari said that the tibetan government - in - exile still has too many disagreements with the chinese government and that there is a very big difference between the positions of the two sides . 
he said that during the past five years the tibetan government - in - exile has tried its best to meet the chinese request for creating a good negotiation environment . 
china should also create a good environment for negotiations on the tibetan issue instead of suppressing the dalai lama unrelentingly . 
he said that the dalai lama does not demand independence for tibet . tibet is still part of china , but the chinese government must preserve tibet 's unique culture so that " tibetans will have genuine autonomy . " 
in addition , lodi gyaltsen gyari noted that some chinese think the tibetan issue will disappear once the dalai lama dies . 
he said that this idea is very dangerous because china will lose a historic opportunity to solve the tibetan issue once the dalai lama passes away . 
he said that as long as the chinese government responds to the requests of the dalai lama and proposes a final resolution , the dalai lama will not need to talk about the tibetan issue internationally . 
negotiation and compromise are important democratic methods ! (zt) 
houze 
i just saw a post by a net friend on the great spirit : to old mr. guiren . 
his / her original words were " negotiation and compromise are important democratic methods , or else , splitting because of disagreements is the failure of democracy ! ! ! i hope idealistic democrats will pay full attention to this point ! " 
this bland remark that has not roused interest among any net friends led me to indulge in a train of thought while all sorts of feelings welled up in my mind . 
at this time , i thought of ancient china as well as the past of the west . 
seldom posting topics , i could not help replying to the post of this net friend in the form of a topic post . 
let 's take a look $number at ancient china . 
everybody knows that beginning with $number qin emperor , china has constructed a large and unified centralized power system , with all dynasties that followed operating under this political framework . 
although a " double - track system " was temporarily implemented in the han dynasty , that is , a political system consisting of a dual coexisting feudal system and centralized power system , after all , there was still a centralized power system in the end . 
the effect of this kind of centralized power system under the conditions at that time in history had its progressive side , had its aspect of promoting the development of forces of production . 
however , we should also see that the prolonged period of $number years of running this system resulted in a lack of creativity , initiative , and activity in local areas , making it even less possible to formulate , based on local conditions , various kinds of regulations and policies appropriate for local development . 
the pyramid - like system of government also caused lower - level officials to only look upward , following every detail of orders from higher levels . 
since all local officials in the county government were appointed by the central government , they had no room for coordination and negotiation among themselves , let alone with those ordinary citizens . 
when their rights were infringed upon , peasants in ancient china could do nothing but put up with it time and again . 
only when their most basic rights were threatened , that is , when their rights of existence were deprived by widespread famine , tyranny , and natural disasters , would they rise in revolt with sharpened sticks . 
over $number years , several peasant uprisings spread like storms across the country , from the spontaneous chen sheng wu guang uprising to the plotted yellow turban uprising , to the huang chao riot in the tang dynasty , as well as the one - month dynastic rule as a result of li zicheng 's uprising . except for zhu yuanzhang , none achieved victory in the true sense of the word . 
even the ming dynasty established this way by zhu yuanzhang was still nothing but a rotating replacement of other dynasties , with no change in the system . 
born a commoner with little education , zhu yuanzhang implemented ancient china 's centralized power system to a sickening extreme . the brimming vitality characteristic of the tang dynasty , born of openness , freedom , and tolerance , was replaced by stagnant lifelessness . 
the free speech atmosphere vanished from the land of china for some time . 
human nature suffered utmost suppression . 
everyone became overcautious and dared not talk too much , from fear and trepidation . 
the result of this sole successful peasant uprising $number years turned the chinese people into subhuman beings for a period of time . 
now let 's take a look at the middle ages in western europe , known as the dark ages . 
the middle ages in western europe was a period of $number years which came about after western rome was destroyed by nomads and had nothing to do with the previous ancient greece and rome . 
this period was characterized by fiefdoms , namely land fiefdoms . 
landlords at lower levels had more independent power . 
whether they were small feudal lords with territories extending a few kilometers or the nobility of dukes , marquises , counts , viscounts , and barons who appeared on formal occasions , as people of various ranks were able to mutually check and balance and depend on one another , with the conditions and abilities to fight for their legitimate rights from the king , there were scenes of kings and noblemen sitting together for negotiations of their own respective interests , scenes never s 
they made mutual compromises and concessions instead of overthrowing or superseding other parties by using force . 
this way , by means of various kinds of contracts , rights were continuously granted to noblemen and commoners , and with increasing power for noblemen and commoners , the king 's rights became increasingly diminished . 
in the end , the british queen became only ceremonial , with no actual power . 
democracy was gradually realized through this method ! 
let 's come back to make a comparison with ancient china , with all power centralized in the hands of the emperor ( except for li shimin ) and with almost no noblemen . it would be hard for peasants to sit with the king at the negotiating table over a cup of tea and a glass of wine , making mutual compromises and concessions in a relaxed and pleasant manner and formulating contracts to the satisfaction of the two sides . 
under such circumstances , when the right of existence was deprived , the only way remaining was to overthrow the existing dynasty by force and try to replace it . 
consequently , there was a repeated rotation , from the heyday of the tang dynasty to the morbidity of the ming dynasty . 
comparing chinese history with western history , we find there seems to be no western country where conflict between the ruler and the ruled was as aggravated as it was in ancient china . 
in no western country were peasant uprisings as frequent as in ancient china . 
in western countries , when conflicts between ancient royal households and peasants arose , noblemen and commoners would $number think of achieving resolution through negotiations to protect their own interests . they would make some mutual concessions to gradually win more rights , while force was rarely used . 
understanding this , you will see that even as we enter $date , some democratic " fighters " on the internet , having inherited the idea of the ultra , absolute totalitarian system of the ming dynasty , 
and also because their bodies are eroded by the poison of the cultural revolution , these democratic " fighters " can talk about nothing except annihilation and overthrow . 
yet it is this kind of ideology that is the largest obstacle to democracy , because these people don 't understand that negotiation , consultation , and compromise are the most important methods and approaches for realizing democracy . 
cao xiaoming : who foots bill for enriching rural cultural activities ? 
houze 
this spring festival , this writer was lucky enough to spend the holiday in rural china and visit some relatives and friends . 
while impressed by the rich festive atmosphere in rural china , i was also concerned with the drab cultural activities in the countryside . 
this writer found in one village with friends and relatives that previously at spring festival each year , this village would spontaneously organize villagers to put on a local theatrical show called " revolving lantern . " 
both adults and children could play roles in this show based on characters in the three warring kingdoms . the villagers never grew tired of watching it . 
there were several performing teams for " revolving lantern " across the township . they not only performed in their own villages but also visited other villages , creating liveliness through their exchanges . 
however , this year this village no longer organized it . 
it turned out that a large sum of money was needed for purchasing costumes alone for " revolving lantern . " in the past , costumes were bought through fund raising among the villagers , yet they are now too worn out to wear . 
asking villagers door to door for money again , nobody wanted to do it . similar situations also occurred in several other villages across the township . 
without the " revolving lantern , " the village suddenly became cold and cheerless . 
adults started to play mahjong . 
children also started to play poker . 
villagers all said there was nothing going on for this new year festival . 
setting off firecrackers or playing mahjong has now become one of the major features of the new year celebration in rural areas . 
meanwhile , gambling persists in spite of numerous bans and is tending to spread further . winning or losing as much as $number yuan in a single game has even become commonplace . in particular , a large number of peasants returning from their migrant jobs outside have become major players at gambling houses . 
their money earned by their own sweat over a whole year thereby goes down the drain . 
in addition , gambling - related family disputes frequently occur . some even lead to tragedies of divorce and death . 
some peasants say they gamble not only during the new year festival , but also frequently participate in gambling during the slack season . 
there is no place to go if they don 't gamble . 
it is too difficult to organize some cultural activities , to find some fun in rural areas . 
there are neither facilities nor funds , but also there are no people acting as organizers . 
however , in this regard , what jiangxi has done is doubtlessly good news for peasants . 
in order to enrich the cultural life of the peasant population , the jiangxi provincial government , starting in $date of last year , not only implemented " theatrical performances funded by the government , operated by the market , supported by townships , provided for peasant enjoyment , " 
but is also allocating at least $number yuan annually to a special fund for rural cultural enterprises , so as to bring high - quality cultural products to the rural population . 
at the start of the new year , $number yuan was again added , bringing the total amount to $number yuan for the establishment of the special fund for rural cultural enterprise . 
moreover , the " bills " paid with this special fund are for real benefits : 
inviting various kinds of professional artistic troupes to stage performances in rural areas , with at least four performances per year in each township ; 
inviting various movie theater companies to dispatch teams to put on movies in rural areas , with at least six dramas and educational science movies per year in each administrative village ; 
organizing and carrying out mass cultural activities with local characteristics , with at least $number events per year in each township . 
from this " purchase inventory list , " it is easy for us to see that the government is not simply providing funds , but trying its best to think about how to use the limited funding to provide what is most needed and to bring value - added cultural enjoyment for the vast rural population . it has done a real job . 
currently , the vast numbers of peasants are rejoicing about being exempt from paying grain tax to the government . 
if the government can do what jiangxi did to " foot the bill " for enriching rural people 's cultural activities , it will be another joy from heaven for peasants . 
furthermore , this " joy " will not only get peasants away from the mahjong table but also get them " active " in cultural activities , which helps add contributions to the construction of new socialist rural areas . 
