( winter olympic games : stimulant ) news analysis : pyleva incident might be settled by leaving it unsettled 
xinhua news agency , turin , $date . news analysis : pyleva incident might be settled by leaving it unsettled 
xinhua news agency reporters : gao peng , ding ying 
although italy reiterated that any athletes who are discovered using stimulants may face the " disaster of being jailed , " many cases currently demonstrate that it is unlikely to happen to russian women 's biathlon athlete olga pyleva , who is at the center of $number scandal over stimulant use at the winter olympic games . 
$number stimulant use scandal at the turin winter olympic games was exposed on the $number , and olga pyleva was discovered to have used the illegal and banned drug carphedon . 
the next day , the international olympic committee announced that pyleva had been thrown out of the winter olympic games , and the silver medal she won for the $number km women 's biathlon had been withdrawn . 
the same day , the international winter biathlon alliance determined to forbid pyleva to participate in the sport for two years . 
the international olympic committee has been implementing the regulation that once athletes are discovered using stimulants , they will lose their qualification to participate in the games , and the scores they achieved will be withdrawn , but they are not subject to legal punishment . 
however , according to italian law , the carrying and use of stimulants by any athlete are criminal activities . a law enforcement organization has the right to directly arrest and investigate any athlete who uses stimulants . any violators of the law are subject to jail for $number months to $number years . 
the international olympic committee had been " bargaining " with the italian government for one year , and eventually reached an agreement last $date . both sides agreed that during the period of the winter olympic games , any athletes who use stimulants would be handled according to italian laws . 
through the unremitting efforts made by the international olympic committee , the italian side made a compromise four days before the opening ceremonies of the winter olympic games , and promised that the police would not enter the olympic village to search athlete residences during the olympic games . but any athletes whose drug tests show positive will be investigated by italian prosecution organizations . 
some reports said that pescante , an official of the italian government responsible for supervision of the turin winter olympic games , has transferred pyleva 's stimulant case to a turin prosecution organization . 
however , the international olympic committee and pescante himself have not confirmed this so far . 
andrey dmytriev , a doctor for the russian biathlon team , disclosed at noontime on the $number that pyleva had left turin and returned home . 
shi kangcheng , a chinese sports official who had been in a position at the world anti - stimulant organization for many years , thinks that once pyleva returns home , this case might eventually " be settled by leaving it unsettled . " 
shi kangcheng said that the international olympic committee and the italian government have not " completely addressed " the anti - stimulant issue at the winter olympic games , and it is hard to say what the outcome would be even if italian prosecution organizations really did get involved in the case . 
based on past penalty cases in which italy sentenced or punished its own athletes who used stimulants , the most serious penalty was merely a " two - year probation . " 
thus , senior reporter piali from the italian ansa said that the possibility of pyleva being jailed is " very small , " and at most , she might be fined . 
piali also said that although an italian court could sentence her by default , it is impossible for the italian police to catch pyleva abroad and bring her back to serve the sentence . 
if pyleva refuses to accept the sentence , the italian side can do nothing about it . 
