& lt ; headline & gt ; the key tools of democracy : negotiation and compromise ! (zt) 
& lt ; poster & gt ; hou ze 
i 've just read a web friend 's posting in " awe - inspiring righteousness - - mr. li guiren " 
his ( her ) original words were " negotiation and compromise are key tools of democracy . otherwise , divisions due to differences of opinion result in the failure of democracy ! ! ! it is hoped that idealistic democracy advocates will pay close attention to this point ! " 
that this prosaic and colorless statement did not attract the interest of any web friends stired a succession of thoughts in my mind and filled me with regret . 
i think about china 's antiquity . i also think about the past in the west . 
i , who have started very few threads , could not resist using a new thread to respond to the posting by the original net friend . 
let 's $number take a look at antiquity in china . 
everybody knows that in china , starting with the united centralized rule built by qin shi huang , all subsequent dynasties operated according to this political framework . 
although the han dynasty temporarily implemented a " dual system " ; that is , political system in which feudalism and centralism operated in parallel ; it finally ended up employing centralism . 
under the historical conditions of that time , this kind of centralism had facets that were advanced or that promoted productivity and development . 
but we should also observe that $number years of this kind of system resulted in localities that lacked the creativity , initiative and motivation that they should have . furthermore , it was impossible to tailor - make systems and policies so that they suited local development . 
a pyramid - shaped system of political rule also made it so that lower - level officials could only fix their gazes upward and in every regard take orders from their immediate superiors . 
because the local county officials were all appointed by the central government , there was no room for coordination or negotiation between them , let alone with the common people . 
when the rights of peasants in ancient china were infringed upon , they could only grin and bear it . 
it was only when their most basic rights were threatened , such as by large scale famine , or when their right to life was being deprived due to tyranny or natural calamity , that they would rise in rebellion . 
in $number years , several turbulent peasant uprisings have swept across the entire country : from the unplanned chen sheng and wu guang uprising to the preplanned yellow turban rebellion , and then to the huang chao rebellion in the tang dynasty and li zicheng , who was able to rule as emperor for a month as the result of an uprising . besides zhu yuanzhang , none of the rebellions obtained a truly meaningful victory . 
even the ming dynasty that zhu yuanzhang initiated was nothing more than the reincarnation of previous dynasties , with no change in political institutions . 
zhu yuanzhang , born a commoner and uncultured for the most part , manipulated china 's ancient centralized system with a perverse relish , taking it to its extreme limits . the vigor of the tang dynasty , characterized by openness , freedom and tolerance , was lost and replaced by a deathly spiritlessness . 
all at once , the atmosphere of free speech disappeared from china 's vast area . 
human nature was suppressed to the highest degree . 
people became timorous , extremely afraid , and unwilling to say too much . 
this was the outcome of the only peasant uprising to succeed in $number years : in one go it turned the chinese people into the living dead . 
now let 's look at western europe 's medieval period , which has been called the dark ages . 
the middle ages in western europe was $number year period that occurred after nomadic peoples destroyed western rome and that did not have the slightest connection to ancient greece and ancient rome . 
this period was characterized by feudalism ; that is , the granting of feudal land titles . 
as titles were subdivided into increasingly lower strata , the lords at each lower stratum possessed an increased amount of autonomy . 
because they were capable of balancing , restricting and depending on each other both vertically and horizontally , even feudal lords with a few square kilometers of land as well as the dukes , marquises , earls , viscounts and barons that came to power possessed the conditions and clout to win from the king the rights that were rightfully theirs , thereby producing a situation where aristocrats and the king sat together to negotiate for their respective benefit , a situation that has ne 
that is , mutual accommodation and concession , and not the use of violent methods to beat down and replace the other party . 
in this way , with the drawing up various agreements , power steadily moved down into the hands of aristocrats and commoners . the power of the aristocrats and commoners gradually increased while the king 's power progressively decreased . 
by the time the queen of england came along , she only occupied a passive position and did not have any real power . 
this is how democracy was gradually achieved ! 
let 's take another look back in order to make a comparison . in ancient china , with all power concentrated in the hand of the emperor ( with the exception of li shimin ) and almost no aristocracy , it was almost impossible for peasants to sit with the emperor over a pot of tea or a glass of wine and light - heartedly make mutual compromises and concessions or formulate agreements that satisfied both sides . 
under such circumstances , when they were being deprived of their right to life , they had no choice but to adopt violent methods to overthrow the current dynasty in an attempt to supplant it . 
this outcome repeated itself again and again , from the high point of the tang dynasty to the morbidity of the ming dynasty . 
if we compare european and chinese history , we discover that there is practically no western country with an ancient period where the contradictions between the rulers and the ruled were as sharp as in china . 
there is no western country that experienced an endless succession of peasant uprisings like china did . 
when contradictions arose between the royal house and the peasants in the ancient history of western countries , $number thing that aristocrats and commoners thought of when they were making an appeal for their own interests was to reach a solution through negotiation and make mutual concessions in order to gradually obtain greater benefits . rarely did they employ violent methods . 
understanding this , as we enter $date , we can still see on the internet that there are some democracy militants who , having inherited the ultra - absolute totalitarian thinking of the ming dynasty , 
and whose bodies have been invaded by the poison of the cultural revolution , are incapable as democratic warriors of talking about anything but " overthrow " and " toppling " . 
but this kind of thinking is the greatest barrier to democracy , because these people do not understand that negotiation and cooperation are the most important means and channel to realizing democracy . 
& lt ; headline & gt ; cao xiaoming - - rich cultural activities in the countryside : who will " pay the bill " ? 
& lt ; poster & gt ; hou ze 
during this year 's spring festival , i was fortunate enough to spend the new year in the countryside visiting some family and friends . 
while being caught up in the rich new year 's atmosphere in china 's countryside , i also became worried about the lack of interesting cultural activities in rural areas . 
i discovered in a friend 's village that in past years the village would set out on its own each spring festival to organize the villagers in putting on a local play called " the galloping horse lantern " . 
the play takes as its subject the characters from the three kingdoms . adults and children can all enact a role in the play . the villagers never tire of watching . 
in this way , there are several " galloping horse lantern " performance troupes throughout the county . they perform not only in their own village , but also travel to other villages , with the exchange between villages becoming very lively . 
but this year the village did not organize a troupe . 
, it seems that it took a lot of money just to buy the costumes for " the galloping horse lantern " . in the past , the villagers would each contribute some cash , but now the costumes are tattered to the point that they can no longer be worn . 
a house - to - house appeal was made to the villagers to again fork out money , but none was willing . a similar situation has arisen in other villages throughout the county . 
without the " galloping horse lantern " , the village has suddenly become cold and cheerless . 
the adults have started playing mahjong . 
the children have also started playing cards . 
the villagers all say that this new year 's was dull . 
other than setting off firecrackers , everybody just played mahjong and that became the general backdrop of chinese new year in the countryside . 
in addition , repeated bans have failed to halt a gambling craze that is showing a tendency to spread . games involving upwards of $number yuan have become a common occurrence , with the large number of returning migrant workers playing a particularly important role in many games . 
in this way , money earned from a year of hard work is squandered . 
also , family squabbles stemming from gambling sometimes occur . some even descend into tragedies where families are split or life is lost . 
some farmers say that they gamble not only during the spring festival , but also often during the slack season . 
if they don 't gamble , they don 't have anywhere to go . 
in the countryside , it is too difficult to organize cultural activities or find entertainment . 
not only is there a lack of facilities and funds , but also nobody volunteers to handle the organization . 
in this respect , the method used in jiangxi is doubtlessly welcome news for rural dwellers . 
in order to enrich the cultural life of the rural population , the jiangxi provincial government has not only implemented as of $date last year a program of " government funding , market operation , town construction of stages and villagers watching plays " , 
but also organizes each year a special fund of at least rmb60 million for rural cultural projects in order to provide the rural population high quality cultural products . 
with the new year , it added an additional rmb40 million , making a rural cultural project fund totaling rmb100 million . 
for the rural population , the fruits of this special fund are also very substantial : 
they invite various types of professional performance troupes to come to the villages to perform . each village cannot have less than four performances each year . 
they invite screening teams from different levels of movie companies and organizations to come to the villages to show movies . each administrative village cannot have less than six screenings of entertainment and educational films each year . 
they organize and hold popular cultural events that have local character . each village cannot have less than two or three each year . 
from this " purchase list " , we can easily see that the government has not thrown money at the problem , but rather has expended a lot of energy to use limited funds in an incisive way in order to deliver a cultural feast with good value to the vast rural population . they have performed an important task . 
now , not an individual among the vast rural population is not ecstatic about the waiver of the grain tax . 
if governments could do like jiangxi and make greater " purchases " to enrich the cultural life of the rural population , it would be another gift from heaven for those living in the countryside , 
and this " gift " would not only free the farmers from the mahjong table , the movement in cultural activities would also add another brick in socialist construction of a new countryside . 
